summary:
I am an applied Mathematician. I completed my PhD in 2018  at The University of Auckland in New Zealand. After that, I moved to Chile and took a one-year research break in which I was mostly dedicated to teaching, my newborn daughter and to apply for research grants. Between 2019 and 2020 I conducted research  at Universidad Técnica Federico Santa María in Chile, funded by the Agencia Nacional de Investigación y Desarrollo (ANID), and since 2021 I am a research associate at Vrije Universiteit Amsterdam, funded by a EPSRC grant on Higher-order interactions and heteroclinic network dynamics.

My research so far lies primarily on the field of dynamical systems and its applications. I like to apply a combination of both analytical and computational tools to understand dynamical phenomena in different contexts. I am motivated by application-driven problems in which you can use math to understand and explain what's going on in real-life contexts. I have always learnt new computational skills on the go as needs arise and always looking for new skills to put in my toolbox. I'm eager to expand the scope of my research, as I'm willing to learn new techniques and methods.  I like to work in an encouraging and challenging environment and team up with motivated people.
 
I have experience on academic research and a vast teaching experience. I have taught math courses for many years to students from different cultural and academic backgrounds, ranging from high school to postgraduate students.
